Analyzing Chicago Traffic Accidents¶

William Cao.

Motivation¶

The Windy City, Chicago is home to 2.71 million residents and is the third largest city in America. With such a large population quite a few of them will drive, and unfortunately many will end up crashing their cars. We will be using the following dataset https://data.cityofchicago.org/Transportation/Traffic-Crashes-Crashes/85ca-t3if/data which includes arround 500k distinct pieces of data from January 2018 to May 2021. Other datasets for different geographical logcations were considered but ultimately we decided to use Chicago's dataset due to it's depth, size, and quality of information provided.

Driving has an important place in American society, even within cities. It symbolizes freedom for the American person, as one is able to go where one wants to when one wants. Analyzing traffic accidents in a city, where driving can be quite tedious and annoying, can help provide insights into helping to keep people safe in addition to keeping premiums low.

Data Gathering¶

We will use quite a few libraries/modules: Pandas for Data manipulation, Matplotlib and Seaborn for Data Visualization. SciPy for Statistical Testing. SciKit-Learn for Machine Learning

The dataset comes in a csv format that we have downloaded from the link above. There are other formats that are possible, but we felt like this was a very natural.

Data Analysis.¶

Lets revisit our speed limit vs crash damage. We note that we have catagorical variables for damage. There are a few ways we could handle it. One way we could handle it would be one hot encoding, where we create a new variable for each catagory and have a binary representation for it. The second way that we are choosing instead is to map the values to continuous variables of 0,750,1500. The reason is that One hot encoding creates extra dimensions, in addition the catagorical variables have a relationship to each other. The damage done to a car can be a continous value.

We choose to first do a linear regression for our data analysis, because it's a fairly simple techique that captures relations that is interpretable and understandable. There are associated pieces of information such as R^2 value where we can understand how much a variable contributes to another variable. There are more complicated models, but Given the limited range of the values of data, they might be overfitting.

We do the following mapping "['500 OR LESS', '501 - 1,500', 'OVER 1,500']" to [0,500,1500] respecitvely, for the lowerbounds of each of the intervals. The reason for this is we want a consistent mappng and 1500 has no upper bound on that interval.

In [199]:
# mapping dictionary
di = {'$500 OR LESS': 0, '$501 - $1,500': 500, 'OVER $1,500': 1500}

To see how effective our model was we used the R^2 value. For reference (https://statisticsbyjim.com/regression/interpret-r-squared-regression/). The r^2ed value captures how much the dependant variable, for us the damage, the is explained by independant variable, the speed limit. In this case only .2% of the damage can be attributed to the speed limit.

One of the probably reasons for this is the courseness of the data. There isn't much diferentiating factors between the larger damage situations. a complete totaling would be the same as having to replace a door for example. With only three catagories perhase there wasn't as much that was able to be picked up from our simple model.

lets try something similar with speed limit but with injuries now, we have less courase data, and we can suspect see that there's a relationship between speed and injury likelyhood, due to kinetic energy increasing with the square of speed.

lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(X,y)

LinearRegression()
In [303]:

We can see that over time the time to report the data has gotten smaller and smaller. We run a linear model on the untransformed model and realize that overall reporting time has gotten faster over time. The tail end reporting times have gotten better over time. However the low value of our regression slope being close to 0 would indicate that while it is improving for the tail end, there isn't a significant ammount of improvement for most of the report times.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion we can see that there some limited relationships between different factors, of which we have explored a few. There are some limitations to the nature of the dataset. One of them is that it only gives times that we crashed. If we wanted to measure how safe something is we would have to do a metric such as crashes per times that a particular section of road is used, or ratio of crash incidents to non crash incidents per car in unit of time. This would require a system of survence cameras to capture this information.

Despite these limitations we have found some interesting pieces of information. For example the distribution of speed limits was centered arround 30. In addition there's fairly weak correlations between many of these variables, which can indicate that there are many factors to crashes. We've explored a few variables to try to see relationships. One of the stronger ones was the number of vehicles and then the lack of injuries. Thankfully from our data in general in many car accidents there are very few injuries at all, which is great news for public safety. In addition we can see that the worst times it took to report an accident have gotten better over time, most of the times have remained fairly consistent.

In addition, there are many parts of the data we could explore in the future. We could explore how time of day impacts collisions. We could explore geolocation and group clusterings of the occurances of the crashes. There are simply many aspects of the data that one could explore further

What we can observe through this is the ability for us to tell a story and communicate ideas through Python. With the tools of visualizations, machine learning, and statistical tests we are better able to dive deep and examine relationships of the world arround us.
